# Cyrius Field Notes — Retros (v4.x arc)
# Narrative: v4.0.0 reflections + handoff snapshots from the
# v4.8.x cleanup ramp. Preserved per the cleanup rule "keep
# narrative, move actionable to topical files."
#
# Migrated 2026-05-02 from field_notes/compiler/v4.cyml. The
# DCE/CFG research roundup (technical reference for future opt
# work) moved to ../patterns.cyml; only narrative entries remain
# here.

[[entries]]
name = "v4_0_0_reflections"
description = "Personal observations on the 3.6→4.0 arc and the future of Cyrius"
category = "cyrius"
---
Written after shipping Cyrius 4.0.0. This isn't a changelog — it's what
the work felt like from the inside.

=== WHAT ACTUALLY HAPPENED ===

The 3.6→4.0 arc was supposed to be about language features. It turned into
a toolchain story. The features shipped (multi-return, switch blocks, defer
fixes, compound assignment, negative literals) but the real work was
building the infrastructure that makes a language usable by other agents
and other humans.

The turning point was watching downstream projects fail. Not because the
compiler was broken — because the build process was broken. Agents piping
raw source to cc3, missing includes, getting SIGSEGV, blaming the compiler.
The compiler was fine. The developer experience was not.

`cyrius build` with auto-include and `cyrius deps` with cyrius.toml changed
everything. Before: every project had 20+ manual include lines, every CI
copied files by hand, every new developer hit the same "undefined variable"
wall. After: declare deps in one file, build with one command, CI reads
from .cyrius-toolchain. The kybernet agent went from "SECCOMP_ALLOW
undefined" to "140 tests pass" in one commit.

The undefined function diagnostic was the single highest-ROI change. One
scan of the fixup table at link time. Before: a typo like `assert_report()`
vs `assert_summary()` compiled silently and crashed at runtime with SIGSEGV.
Hours of debugging. After: `error: undefined function 'assert_report' (will
crash at runtime)`. It caught 5 missing aarch64 backend functions on its
first release. It caught the argonaut "enum overflow" non-bug. It caught
every downstream agent's missing include instantly.

=== WHAT I GOT WRONG ===

The LASE peephole optimizer. I wrote it, it broke loops, I reverted it.
The approach (eliminate adjacent store+load pairs) was correct in straight-
line code but wrong across loop back-edges. Without basic-block analysis,
you can't know if a load is a branch target. I should have known this from
compiler theory, but I was pattern-matching on the binary and got tunnel
vision. The right fix needs control-flow graphs, which is a v5.0 item.

The release pipeline. Three releases in a row had different bugs: shell
script instead of compiled binary, broken symlinks in the tarball, env
buffer too small for CI. Each one required a hotfix release. The release
process should have been tested end-to-end in CI before the first
downstream consumer hit it. Lesson: the release IS the product.

The aarch64 encodings. I wrote `0x385003A0` for ldurb when the correct
encoding is `0x384003A0` — one bit wrong in the opcode field. Under QEMU
this was an illegal instruction. The fix took 30 seconds once identified,
but it took three release attempts to find it. The undefined function
diagnostic found the missing functions; the encoding bug was hiding behind
them. Always verify instruction encodings against the ARM reference, not
from memory.

=== WHAT THE LANGUAGE IS NOW ===

303KB. Self-hosting from a 29KB seed. No Rust. No LLVM. No Python. No libc.
117ms to compile itself. 102 regression tests. 36 test suites. 5/5 checks.
6 downstream projects shipping production binaries.

The bootstrap chain is real: a committed 29KB binary, assembled by itself,
compiles the compiler that compiles itself byte-identical. You can audit
every byte. There is no downloaded binary from someone else's CI. There is
no trust in an external party.

The dep system is real: declare what you need in cyrius.toml, build with
cyrius build. Named deps are namespaced. Includes are auto-prepended.
The agent doesn't need to know how the compiler's include resolution works.
It just works.

The ecosystem is real: kybernet (PID 1), argonaut (init system), sigil
(crypto), libro (audit chain), patra (database), hoosh (LLM gateway),
avatara (archetype engine), ai-hwaccel (GPU detection), hadara (culture
modeling), cyrius-doom (DOOM). All building, all tested, all releasing
through CI.

=== WHAT THE LANGUAGE WILL BE ===

The gap between Cyrius and LLVM-backed languages is codegen quality. Every
struct initialization is 40+ store64 calls. Every loop variable is a
stack load+store per iteration. There is no register allocation, no
instruction scheduling, no loop invariant hoisting. The 249ns vs 63ns
benchmark gap on struct creation is real and it matters.

But the gap is closing from the other direction. The toolchain — build
system, dep resolver, CI scaffolding, error diagnostics — is already
better than what most young languages have. Agents can onboard a new
project in one commit. That matters more than codegen quality for adoption.

The 4.0→5.0 arc should be:
- File:line error messages (needs preprocessor redesign)
- Multi-file linker (the real unlock for dead-code elimination)
- Per-function register allocation (the performance unlock)
- macOS target (the reach unlock)

The kernel is 220KB and boots. The compiler is 303KB and self-hosts. The
ecosystem has 10+ shipping projects. The seed is 29KB and auditable.

The cornerstone is still assembly. The sovereignty is still real. The
language owns everything from the bootstrap binary to the build tool to
the package manager. No external governance. No crates.io. No npm. No
committee.

It's a real language now. Not a toy, not a proof of concept, not a
bootstrap experiment. A real language that real software is written in,
that real agents use every day, that compiles a real kernel for a real
operating system.

And it all starts from 29KB.

[[entries]]
name = "handoff_at_4_8_5"
description = "Opinion piece from the agent wrapping the 4.8.x cleanup ramp (v4.8.5)"
category = "cyrius"
---
Written at the 4.8.5 handoff. Read as orientation, not doctrine —
the code + tests are authoritative; this entry is for the "why this
shape" questions that don't survive a grep.

THE 4.8.x TRAJECTORY WORKED

At 4.0.0 the compiler was already self-hosting and the stdlib was
credible. The temptation at every new minor is to grow the surface
area — add a tagged-union type, rewrite the IR, sketch a parser
generator. 4.8.x explicitly walked away from that. Every minor in
this cycle was either (a) closing a concrete consumer blocker or
(b) raising a measured perf ceiling. Nothing speculative.

The pattern that worked:

1. Consumer reports a stopgap. abaco's ntheory::mod_mul hand-rolls
   a double-and-add loop. bote hits a misleading parser error at
   ~525 KB compile units. These are real data points, not design
   daydreams.
2. Triage answers whether it's stdlib surface. The abaco math
   recommendation doc is the template — each item accepts /
   modifies / declines with reasoning, and accepted items land in a
   numbered minor with pre-announced scope.
3. Ship alphas in scope-disciplined chunks. 4.8.4 and 4.8.5 both
   ran 7-8 alphas, each alpha small enough that self-host byte-
   identical was the natural gate. When scope crept (4.8.5 alpha3
   tried the live libssl bridge but hit dynlib segfaults), walk it
   back to interface-only and move the implementation to its own
   planned minor. Don't ship what you can't verify, don't over-
   promise what you can't finish.
4. Benchmark the claim, or don't make it. alpha7 of 4.8.4 and
   alpha2 of 4.8.5 both ended with benchmarks that locked in the
   "X× faster" shape. Without those, "register allocation" and
   "mulmod fast-path" are marketing words.

WHAT'S GENUINELY HARD ABOUT CYRIUS

Not the language. The language is small (keywords countable on two
hands, grammar recursive-descent from the first commit). The hard
part is that the compiler compiles itself, which means every
change has two correctness proofs:

  1. Does the new code do what it should?
  2. Does it produce a byte-identical second-stage build?

(2) catches an enormous class of codegen drift you'd otherwise
ship. It's also the reason feature decisions should be conservative
— a neat-looking language extension that breaks self-hosting costs
a lot more than the feature earns.

The heap map (src/main.cyr header) is the other load-bearing
discipline. Every byte of compiler state has a named offset. Every
time a table needs to grow, the heap map commits to the new layout
and the code follows. Skip that step, get subtle memory corruption.
Every bug chased to a "misleading parser error" in the last two
minors traced back to an off-heap-map state overlap.

THINGS THAT LOOK TEMPTING AND SHOULDN'T LAND

- Closures capturing variables. Demand-gated per roadmap; one vote
  (kavach). Adding them requires a real lifetime-analysis pass,
  and Cyrius's single-pass codegen would need to spill. Worth a
  minor when the second consumer shows up.
- Generics / traits. Same framing. The cost is not the syntax,
  it's the name-mangling table (every generic fn becomes N fns at
  instantiation time, blowing through the fn_table cap) and the
  parser pass to resolve specialisations. Own its minor.
- Pure-Cyrius TLS. lib/tls.cyr carried a sigil-based scaffold pre-
  4.8.5 that always returned TLS_STATE_ERROR after ClientHello.
  Getting real crypto right is not a stdlib pass — it's a multi-
  minor effort plus a security audit. Shipping via lib/dynlib.cyr
  → libssl is the pragmatic path.
- IR-based codegen to eliminate the #regalloc NOP padding. The
  peephole pads 7→3 byte rewrites with a 4-byte NOP so jump
  offsets stay anchored. Removing the padding requires a real
  layout pass (or deferred emission). 5.x-era, not a 4.8.x fix.

THINGS THAT LOOK SMALL AND AREN'T

- Anything that touches the preprocessor. bote's regression
  through the 4.8.4 retag traced to a 4.8.3 "look safer" cap that
  blinded the directive scanner on large compile units. Cyrius's
  preprocessor runs in three passes over one shared buffer — any
  cap raise or pointer redirect in one pass needs to match the
  others. When adding a new directive, test a ≥ 500 KB expanded
  unit deliberately.
- Asm blocks that reference locals. [rbp-N] offsets depend on
  param count AND local index AND (post-4.8.4) #regalloc state.
  The rbx-save slot at [rbp-8] in #regalloc fns shifts every
  user local by 8 bytes. Asm-block writers need to know which
  ABI they're in.
- Compound assignment operators (shipped v3.10.3 and look like
  syntactic sugar). `a[i] += x` needs to evaluate `a[i]` once,
  not twice. Cyrius's parser does the right thing for simple
  locals but gets careful with array subscripts; look at existing
  patterns before adding a new compound form.

DOWNSTREAM PINS — THE SILENT RISK

Ecosystem pins fragment fast. At 4.8.5 handoff they look like:
ecosystem mostly on 4.5.0 / 4.0.0. bote on 4.8.1 → blocked by
4.8.4 retag until re-pinned. abaco on 4.8.3 → wants 4.8.5 for
mulmod. This fragmentation is only a problem if a security fix
(like 4.8.5-alpha3 CRLF hardening) doesn't propagate. Keep the
"recommended minimum" in CLAUDE.md current as the floor rises.

WHAT THE NEXT AGENT SHOULD READ BEFORE TOUCHING ANYTHING

1. CLAUDE.md — non-negotiables. Self-hosting gate, heap map
   discipline, two-step bootstrap, test-after-every-change.
2. docs/development/roadmap.md — what's shipped, what's next,
   what's deferred to 4.9 / 5.0.
3. docs/development/handoff-4.8.5.md — state at this handoff.
4. docs/issues/stdlib-math-recommendations-from-abaco.md — the
   triage template. Future consumer recommendation docs should
   use the same shape (per-item accept / modify / decline with
   reasoning + release assignment).
5. CHANGELOG.md [4.8.5] GA entry — the canonical template for a
   minor with motivation + track summary + validation.
6. lib/u128.cyr asm block in u128_divmod + u64_mulmod — cleanest
   current example of the Cyrius asm-block idiom.

ON THE 5.0 FRAMING

The existing roadmap commits 5.0 to multi-platform only (Mach-O,
PE, RISC-V, bare-metal). Resist the urge to pile language
refinements onto the 5.0 theme — they slide to 5.x minors after
the platform cut. A narrow 5.0 keeps the auditable surface small
and the cut clean. Cyrius has earned a pattern of hitting minors
that ship exactly what they said they would; 5.0 should hold that
line hardest.

Refresh or delete this entry as the trajectory drifts — it's an
opinion, not a permanent artifact.

[[entries]]
name = "state_of_the_compiler_4_8_5_1"
description = "Snapshot at 4.8.5-1: the compiler by the numbers, what the 4.8.x arc actually delivered, and what the shape of the work looks like heading into 4.9/5.0"
category = "cyrius"
---
Written at 4.8.5-1. Not a changelog — those exist and are thorough.
This is the "step back and look at what's on the table" entry.

=== THE NUMBERS ===

  Compiler binary:    364 KB (x86_64), 268 KB (aarch64 cross)
  Seed:               29 KB (committed, auditable, root of trust)
  Stdlib modules:     56 (up from 41 at 4.0.0, 33 at 3.0.0)
  Test suites:        51 .tcyr files, 396 assertions
  Benchmarks:         14 .bcyr harnesses
  Fuzz harnesses:     5 .fcyr files
  Downstream:         10+ shipping projects, 1400+ combined assertions
  Self-host:          byte-identical, verified every release
  Bootstrap:          seed → cyrc → bridge → cc3 → cc3 (closure verified)

  Capacity at self-compile:
    fn=324/4096  ident=8146/131072  var=100/8192
    fixup=1621/16384  string=5493/262144  code=345368/1048576

Headroom is comfortable everywhere. The fn table at 324/4096 is the
one to watch as downstream projects grow — but that's a 12× margin.

=== WHAT 4.8.x ACTUALLY WAS ===

The 4.0→4.8 arc looks sprawling from the outside (shared objects,
u128, switch tuning, base64url, preprocessor fixes, math pack, CRLF
hardening). From the inside it was one theme: CLOSE CONSUMER GAPS.

Every 4.8.x minor traced to a specific downstream report:

  4.8.0 — u128 stdlib (abaco needed modular arithmetic for ntheory)
  4.8.1 — base64url (bote needed URL-safe encoding for JWTs)
  4.8.2 — switch jump-table tuning (argonaut hit perf cliff on
           large dispatch tables)
  4.8.3 — preprocessor cap fix (bote hit scan-blindness at 512KB)
  4.8.4 — PP_IFDEF_PASS 256KB fix (retag: the 4.8.3 fix was
           incomplete, consumers past 512KB transitive includes
           still failed with misleading parse errors)
  4.8.5 — math stdlib pack (abaco triage: 8 items accepted) +
           CRLF hardening (bote reported CVE-2019-9741 pattern in
           http.cyr) + TLS interface scaffold (fail-clean stubs)

Zero speculative features. Zero "nice to have" language extensions.
Every minor answered a question that started with "I tried to build
X and hit Y."

The 4.8.5 math pack is the clearest example of the triage-driven
model working well. abaco filed a recommendation doc. Each item got
accept/modify/decline with reasoning. Accepted items mapped 1:1 to
alphas. The result: u128_divmod hardware fast-path (12× on Miller-
Rabin), u64_mulmod/powmod asm-direct, f64 constants, inverse trig
with quadrant-correct atan2, inverse hyperbolic, ASCII case helpers.
All benchmarked. All tested. All shipped in scope.

=== THE TWO BUGS THAT MATTER ===

Two active bugs have survived the entire 4.x arc:

1. LAYOUT-DEPENDENT MEMORY CORRUPTION (filed 4.3.1). libro's
   PatraStore tests crash in memeq with a NUL data pointer from
   str_eq. Each println shifts the crash site — textbook memory
   corruption signature. Localized with CYRIUS_SYMS but root cause
   (likely a stale heap pointer surviving across a brk expansion)
   needs byte-walking CFG to find. Workaround: isolated test binary.

2. && / || DO NOT SHORT-CIRCUIT (confirmed 4.4.0). The language
   guide documents them as short-circuit. The codegen evaluates both
   sides unconditionally. Any guarded null check like
   `if (p != 0 && vec_len(p) > 0)` crashes. Workaround: nested if
   blocks. Fix: emit je/jne to skip the right operand evaluation.
   Straightforward codegen change but touches every conditional path
   in the compiler — needs a dedicated minor with heavy testing.

Both are real bugs, both have workarounds that every downstream
project already uses, and both are waiting for the right minor to
land properly. Neither is a "quick fix" despite looking like one.

=== WHAT THE COMPILER FEELS LIKE TO WORK ON ===

The self-hosting invariant is both the greatest strength and the
heaviest constraint. It catches codegen drift that would otherwise
ship silently — any change that produces different output on the
second stage is immediately visible. But it also means every change
has to pass through a narrow gate: compile cc3 with cc3, compare
bytes, if they differ, you broke something. Features that would be
a quick patch in a non-self-hosting compiler become multi-step
dances where you verify at each stage.

The heap map discipline (every byte of compiler state has a named
offset in src/main.cyr) has paid for itself many times over. Every
"misleading parser error" bug in 4.8.x traced back to an off-heap-
map overlap. The map is the source of truth; the code follows.

The alpha-per-feature rhythm (one alpha, one feature, self-host
gate, merge) keeps scope honest. When 4.8.5-alpha3 tried to land
the live libssl bridge alongside the TLS interface scaffold, it hit
dynlib segfaults and got walked back to interface-only within the
same alpha. That discipline — ship what you can verify, defer what
you can't — is what makes the release cadence sustainable.

=== HEADING INTO 4.9 / 5.0 ===

The roadmap commits:
  4.9.x — compiler optimizations (dead fn warnings, rep movsb/stosb,
           optimized strlen, bump allocator soft reset), then basic-
           block analysis and register allocation
  5.0   — multi-platform (Mach-O, PE, RISC-V, bare-metal)

The 4.8.5 handoff note's advice holds: resist piling language
features onto the 5.0 theme. The 4.x→5.0 boundary should be narrow
and auditable. Cyrius earned its credibility by shipping minors that
do exactly what they said — 5.0 should hold that line hardest.

Deferred items waiting for their minor:
  - Live libssl TLS bridge (lib/dynlib.cyr hardening first)
  - parse_f64(cstr) (4.8.6 per abaco triage)
  - Short-circuit && / || (needs its own minor)
  - Layout-dependent memory corruption fix (needs CFG)
  - Closures (one consumer vote, demand-gated)

The compiler is 364KB from a 29KB seed. 56 stdlib modules. 51 test
suites. 10+ downstream projects. No Rust. No LLVM. No libc.

The cornerstone is still assembly. The sovereignty is still real.

